Even *[The Blair Witch Project](/The_Blair_Witch_Project)* (1999), a low-budget independent horror film by [Eduardo Sanchez](/Eduardo_S%C3%A1nchez_(director)) and [Daniel Myrick](/Daniel_Myrick), achieved immense financial success. Produced on a shoestring budget of just $35,000, without any major stars or elaborate special effects, the film grossed $248 million, largely due to innovative marketing techniques and online promotion. While not on the scale of [George Lucas](/George_Lucas)'s $1 billion prequel to the *[Star Wars Trilogy](/Star_Wars_original_trilogy)*, *The Blair Witch Project* earned the distinction of being the most profitable film of all time in terms of percentage return on investment. Despite this outlier success, control of [The Big Five](/Big_Five_(movie_studios)) studios over film production continued to grow throughout the 1990s. The Big Six companies all experienced a period of expansion during this decade. Each developed distinct strategies to manage rising production costs, particularly the escalating salaries demanded by movie stars, often driven by powerful agents. Top stars like [Sylvester Stallone](/Sylvester_Stallone), [Russell Crowe](/Russell_Crowe), [Tom Cruise](/Tom_Cruise), [Nicole Kidman](/Nicole_Kidman), [Sandra Bullock](/Sandra_Bullock), [Arnold Schwarzenegger](/Arnold_Schwarzenegger), [Mel Gibson](/Mel_Gibson), [Kevin Bacon](/Kevin_Bacon), and [Julia Roberts](/Julia_Roberts) commanded salaries between $15–$20 million per film, and in some cases, also secured a share of the film's profits [67].

Screenwriters, conversely, typically earned less than top actors or directors, usually under $1 million per film. However, the single most significant factor driving up costs was special effects. By 1999, the average cost of a [blockbuster film](/Blockbuster_(entertainment)) had reached $60 million, with marketing and promotion adding an additional $80 million [67].

#### Contemporary Cinema

*   This section requires expansion to include other film genres beyond superhero and blockbuster, discussions of studios beyond the A-list, commentary on "superhero fatigue," and details on the 2023 Hollywood labor disputes. Further details may exist on the [talk page](/Talk:Cinema_of_the_United_States). (May 2023)

Since the turn of the 21st century, the theatrical market has been increasingly dominated by the [superhero film](/Superhero_film) genre. As of 2022 [update], these productions offer the highest compensation for actors, as paychecks in other genres have diminished even for top stars [70]. However, in 2023 and 2024, Hollywood experts began to identify 'superhero fatigue' as an emerging trend [71]. Actors such as [Paul Dano](/Paul_Dano) and directors like [Matthew Vaughn](/Matthew_Vaughn) have echoed these sentiments [72][73].

In 2021, despite the ongoing [COVID-19 pandemic in the United States](/COVID-19_pandemic_in_the_United_States), major blockbuster films such as *[Black Widow](/Black_Widow_(2021_film))* , *[F9](/F9_(film))* , *Death on the Nile*, and *West Side Story* were released in theaters after postponements from their original 2020 release dates [74].

Various studios responded to the crisis with controversial decisions to [forgo the theatrical window](/Film_distribution) and offer their films [day-and-date releases](/Simultaneous_release). [NBCUniversal](/NBCUniversal) released *[Trolls World Tour](/Trolls_World_Tour)* directly to [video-on-demand](/Video_on_demand) rental on April 10 [75], while simultaneously offering limited domestic theatrical screenings via drive-in cinemas [76]. CEO [Jeff Shell](/Jeff_Shell) claimed the film generated nearly $100 million in revenue within its first three weeks [77][78]. This decision was met with opposition from [AMC Theatres](/AMC_Theatres), which announced it would cease screening Universal Pictures films immediately, though the two companies eventually reached an agreement on a two-week theatrical window [79][80][81][82][83]. By December 2020, [Warner Bros. Pictures](/Warner_Bros._Pictures) announced its plan to simultaneously release its entire 2021 film slate, including *[Dune](/Dune_(2021_film))* and *[The Matrix Resurrections](/The_Matrix_Resurrections)*, in both theaters and its streaming service [HBO Max](/HBO_Max) for a one-month period to maximize viewership [84]. However, by 2023, industry strikes by the Writers Guild of America (WGA) and the Screen Actors Guild (SAG-AFTRA) highlighted escalating disputes over streaming residuals, the use of artificial intelligence in writing and acting, and fair compensation, reflecting the broader challenges confronting Hollywood's evolving economic model. This decision by Warner Bros. was vehemently criticized by numerous industry figures, many of whom reportedly felt blindsided and deceived by the studio [85].

The period from 2019 onwards has witnessed the rise of American streaming platforms, such as [Netflix](/Netflix), [Disney+](/Disney%2B), [Paramount+](/Paramount%2B), and [Apple TV+](/Apple_TV%2B), which have emerged as significant competitors to traditional cinema. Industry commentators have observed a growing tendency to treat films as "[content](/Content_(media))" by corporations, a trend that correlates with the increased popularity of streaming platforms [86][87]. This involves a blurring of the lines between films, television, and other media as audiences consume them in diverse ways. Individual films are increasingly defined by their brand identity and commercial potential rather than their inherent medium, narrative, or artistic merit [86][89]. Critic [Matt Zoller Seitz](/Matt_Zoller_Seitz) described the 2019 release of *[Avengers: Endgame](/Avengers:_Endgame)* as "represent[ing] the decisive defeat of 'cinema' by 'content'" due to its immense success as a "piece of entertainment" defined by the Marvel brand, culminating a series of blockbuster films that exhibit traits of serialized television [86].

[Tom Cruise](/Tom_Cruise), in a pre-recorded segment, skydived from the [Stade de France](/Stade_de_France) to the [Hollywood Sign](/Hollywood_Sign), where he landed and affixed the five Olympic rings, marking the handover of the [Games to Los Angeles](/2028_Summer_Olympics) in 2028 during the [2024 Summer Olympics closing ceremony](/2024_Summer_Olympics_closing_ceremony). Cruise himself has been cited as a paragon of modern cinema, with *[Top Gun: Maverick](/Top_Gun:_Maverick)* being lauded as one of the first blockbuster films to achieve significant monetary success despite facing low expectations and competition from other franchise films and streaming platforms.

Films such as *[Space Jam: A New Legacy](/Space_Jam:_A_New_Legacy)* and *[Red Notice](/Red_Notice_(film))* have been cited as examples of this trend. The former has been described by many critics as "a lengthy infomercial for HBO Max," featuring scenes and characters referencing various Warner Bros. properties like *[Casablanca](/Casablanca_(film))* , *[The Matrix](/The_Matrix)* , and *[Austin Powers](/Austin_Powers)* [90][91][92][93]. The latter, a $200 million heist film from Netflix, has been described by critics as "a movie that feels more processed by a machine [...] instead of anything approaching artistic intent or even an honest desire to entertain" [94][95][96]. Some critics argue that *Space Jam* exemplifies the industry's increasingly cynical approach of treating films as mere intellectual property (IP) to be exploited, a strategy that critic Scott Mendelson termed "IP for the sake of IP" [91][97][98][92].

[Martin Scorsese](/Martin_Scorsese) has voiced concerns that cinema as an art form is "being systematically devalued, sidelined, demeaned, and reduced" to mere "content" and has called the overemphasis on box-office returns for blockbusters "repulsive" [99][100]. [Quentin Tarantino](/Quentin_Tarantino) has opined that the current era of cinema is one of the worst in Hollywood history [101][102]. During a masterclass at the 2023 [Sarajevo Film Festival](/Sarajevo_Film_Festival), [Charlie Kaufman](/Charlie_Kaufman) criticized mainstream blockbusters, stating that "[a]t this point, the only thing that makes money is garbage" and urged industry professionals to "make movies outside of the studio system as much as possible" [103][104]. In an interview with [Deadline](/Deadline_Hollywood), [James Gray (director)](/James_Gray_(director)) noted, "When you make movies that only make a ton of money and only one kind of movie, you begin to get a large segment of the population out of the habit of going to the movies," which leads to decreased viewership. He clarified that he has "no problem with a comic book movie" but suggests that studios "be willing to lose money for a couple of years on art film divisions, and in the end they will be happier" as a solution to the lack of "investment in the broad-based engagement with the product" [105].

#### Hollywood and Politics

*   Main article: [Good Neighbor policy](/Good_Neighbor_policy)

The 81st [Academy Awards](/Academy_Awards) ceremony held at the [Dolby Theatre](/Dolby_Theatre) in [Hollywood, Los Angeles](/Hollywood,_Los_Angeles) in 2009.

In the 1930s and 1940s, both the [Democrats](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) and the [Republicans](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) recognized the political opportunities within Hollywood. President [Franklin Roosevelt](/Franklin_Roosevelt) was an early adopter, effectively leveraging the charisma of Hollywood stars in national campaigns [106]. [Melvyn Douglas](/Melvyn_Douglas) and his wife Helen embarked on a tour of Washington, D.C., in 1939, where they met with key figures of the New Deal administration [107].

##### Political Endorsements

*   See also: [Hollywood blacklist](/Hollywood_blacklist) and [List of Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign celebrity endorsements](/List_of_Joe_Biden_2020_presidential_campaign_celebrity_endorsements)

Endorsement letters from prominent actors were solicited and signed, and appearances on radio programs and printed advertisements were utilized to amplify political messages. Movie stars were strategically employed to draw large audiences to engage with the political perspectives of the parties. By the 1960s, [John F. Kennedy](/John_F._Kennedy) represented a fresh, youthful presence in Washington, and his close friendship with [Frank Sinatra](/Frank_Sinatra) epitomized this new era of glamour. The old guard of Hollywood moguls had faded, and younger, emerging executives and producers began championing more [liberal](/Modern_liberalism_in_the_United_States) ideas [108][109].

The allure of celebrities and the perceived affluence of the glittering Hollywood lifestyle attracted politicians. As [Ron Brownstein](/Ron_Brownstein) observed in his book *The Power and the Glitter*, television emerged as a profoundly influential new medium in politics during the 1970s and 1980s, and Hollywood played a significant role in this landscape. Actors such as [Jane Fonda](/Jane_Fonda) delivered speeches articulating their political beliefs, notably in opposition to the Vietnam War [110]. Despite the predominantly left-leaning political leanings of most celebrities and producers, who tended to support the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [111][112], this era also produced notable [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) actors and producers, including [Clint Eastwood](/Clint_Eastwood) and [Jerry Bruckheimer](/Jerry_Bruckheimer). Support groups like the [Friends of Abe](/Friends_of_Abe) were established to champion conservative causes within Hollywood, an industry often perceived as biased against conservatives [113]. Former actor [Ronald Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan) successfully transitioned into politics, becoming [governor of California](/Governor_of_California) and subsequently the 40th president of the United States. This trend continued with [Arnold Schwarzenegger](/Arnold_Schwarzenegger) serving as California's governor in [2003](/2003_California_gubernatorial_recall_election).

##### Political Donations

The [Academy Museum of Motion Pictures](/Academy_Museum_of_Motion_Pictures).

Today, donations from Hollywood contribute significantly to funding federal politics. For instance, on February 20, 2007, then-presidential candidate [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama) hosted a Hollywood gala at the Beverly Hilton, with a ticket price of $2,300 per plate, organized by [DreamWorks](/DreamWorks_Pictures) founders [David Geffen](/David_Geffen), [Jeffrey Katzenberg](/Jeffrey_Katzenberg), and [Steven Spielberg](/Steven_Spielberg) [115].

#### Criticisms

##### Covert Advertising

[Native advertising](/Native_advertising) is designed to persuade through subtle means, distinguishing it from overt propaganda. A prevalent modern example in the United States is [Copaganda](/Copaganda), where television shows often present unrealistically flattering portrayals of law enforcement. This practice serves, in part, to facilitate the borrowing of equipment and obtain assistance in blocking off streets for easier filming on location [116]. Other accusations of [reputation laundering](/Reputation_laundering) have been leveled against the entertainment industry, including efforts to enhance the image of the Mafia [117].

[Product placement](/Product_placement) has also been a point of criticism, particularly concerning the tobacco industry's promotion of smoking on screen [118]. The [Centers for Disease Control and Prevention](/Centers_for_Disease_Control_and_Prevention) estimates that 18% of teen smokers would not have started smoking if films depicting smoking were automatically given an 'R' rating, a measure that could potentially save one million lives [119].

##### Censorship

*   See also: [Overseas censorship of Chinese issues](/Overseas_censorship_of_Chinese_issues) and [List of TV and films critical of Chinese Communist Party](/List_of_TV_and_films_critical_of_Chinese_Communist_Party)

Hollywood producers sometimes acquiesce to the censorship requirements of the [Chinese government](/Chinese_government) in an effort to gain access to the country's lucrative and restricted cinema market [120], which, as of 2016, was the second-largest box office globally. This can involve prioritizing sympathetic portrayals of Chinese characters in films, such as altering the villains in *[Red Dawn](/Red_Dawn_(2012_film))* from Chinese to North Koreans [120]. Due to the numerous topics forbidden in China, such as the Dalai Lama and [Winnie-the-Pooh](/Winnie-the-Pooh) being referenced in the *[South Park](/South_Park)* episode "[Band in China](/Band_in_China)", *South Park* was completely banned in China following the episode's broadcast [121]. The 2018 film *[Christopher Robin](/Christopher_Robin_(film))* , a new Winnie-the-Pooh movie, was denied a release in China [121].

While [Tibet](/Tibet) was once a prominent cause célèbre in Hollywood, featured in films like *[Kundun](/Kundun)* and *[Seven Years in Tibet](/Seven_Years_in_Tibet)*, this has diminished in the 21st century [122]. In 2016, [Marvel Entertainment](/Marvel_Entertainment) faced criticism for casting Tilda Swinton as "The Ancient One" in the film adaptation *[Doctor Strange](/Doctor_Strange_(2016_film))* , a decision seen by some as whitewashing by casting a white actress in a traditionally Tibetan role [123]. Actor and prominent Tibet supporter [Richard Gere](/Richard_Gere) stated he was no longer welcome in mainstream Hollywood films after criticizing the Chinese government and calling for a boycott of the [2008 Summer Olympics](/2008_Summer_Olympics) in Beijing [122][124].

###### Historic Examples

Hollywood also engaged in self-censorship, avoiding negative depictions of Nazis for most of the 1930s to maintain access to the German market [125]. Around that time, [economic censorship](/Economic_censorship) led to the [self-censoring](/Self-censorship) of content to appease influential groups. The [Hays Code](/Hays_Code), an industry-led initiative from 1930 to 1967, enforced strict self-censorship to appease religious objections and preempt government intervention [125].

